Operations look like pandas.

The whole appeal of the pandas interface on Spark is that your familiar pandas idioms just work. Filtering, projecting, grouping — they all read the way they do in ordinary pandas.

You filter with boolean indexing, writing a condition inside the brackets to keep the rows that match. You select a column and call value counts to get a tally of how often each value appears. And you group by a column and aggregate, using named aggregations to spell out the result columns you want.

The important thing to picture is what happens underneath. None of this is really running pandas. Each of these operations translates down into Spark dataframe operations, and they execute lazily — the same lazy model as the rest of Spark. You write pandas; the cluster runs Spark.
